06258nam a22010215i 9780674293465DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742934657 a10.4159/97806742934652doi  a(DE-B1597)642348  a(OCoLC)1376361915  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aRA425b.H588 2023eb 7aHEA0490002bisacsh04a614.4/2223/eng/202210071 aHood, Leroy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Age of Scientific Wellness :bWhy the Future of Medicine Is Personalized, Predictive, Data-Rich, and in Your Hands /cLeroy Hood, Nathan Price. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 An Infectious Idea -- t2 Catalyzing the Revolution -- t3 Mining Vast Troves of Information -- t4 Measuring and Tracking Health -- t5 A New Way to Think about How Old We Are -- t6 Keeping Our Minds Healthy for Life -- t7 The Long Goodbye -- t8 Deciphering Dementia -- t9 Cancers at a Turning Point -- t10 The AI Imperative -- t11 The Path Forward -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTaking us to the cutting edge of the new frontier of medicine, a visionary biotechnologist and a pathbreaking researcher show how we can optimize our health in ways that were previously unimaginable.We are on the cusp of a paradigm shift in the delivery of health care as major diseases are being challenged in fresh and unexpected ways. Using predictive technologies, applied immunotherapy, and genomically informed disease prevention, scientists are working closely with patients to dramatically extend their “healthspan”—the number of healthy years before disease sets in. Leroy Hood, whose innovations made possible the sequencing of the human genome, and Nathan Price, whose work on systems biology is opening new pathways to Alzheimer’s treatment and prevention, take us on a thrilling journey to this new frontier of medicine.Today, most doctors wait for clinical symptoms to appear before they act. Countless patients are prescribed medication and subjected to invasive procedures from which they derive no benefit. We must move beyond this reactive, hit-or-miss approach to usher in real precision care or “scientific wellness.” Fusing information gleaned from our personal genomic profiles with data drawn from our blood, microbiomes, and hundreds of other inputs, all analyzed by artificial intelligence, doctors can detect the early onset of disease decades before symptoms arise, revolutionizing prevention. Current applications have already shown startling results: Alzheimer’s held back, cancers found early and eliminated, diabetes avoided, and autoimmune diseases neutralized.Genomically informed medicine is not some future fantasy: it is already happening at top medical centers, but only for a narrow band of diseases and only once they are well advanced. This book shares the insights of this exciting new science to help you chart a course to a longer, healthier life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDiagnostic services. 0aHealth status indicators. 0aMedicine, Preventive. 0aPreventive health servicesxTechnological innovations. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Longevity .2bisacsh  abig data.  abiological aging.  abiomarkers.  abrain.  acholesterol.  achronic.  acognition.  acovid 19.  adementia.  adiagnosis.  adna.  ahuman genome.  aimmune system.  ainfectious.  alife expectancy.  ametabolism.  aneuroplasticity.  ap4 medicine.  aphenome.  aphenotyping.1 aPrice, Nathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator